This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with action recognition and segmentation using skeleton-based data streams. It also involves the use of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) which are commonly used in computer vision tasks. 

The paper also involves deep learning frameworks, which makes it likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. 

The use of interpretable patterns in the data suggests that the paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. 

The evaluation of the proposed framework on real-world benchmarks suggests that it may belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. 

Finally, the use of filters trained based on their alignments to local subsequences in the inputs suggests that the paper may also belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
